Network Printing Troubleshooting: April 2026 Quick Guide

Network printing in April 2026 relies on modern protocols. Legacy discovery methods like NetBIOS and SMBv1 
are blocked by default. If your printer isn't found, confirm it supports mDNS/Bonjour or WSD over HTTPS. Update 
printer firmware via the manufacturer's portal; devices older than 2018 may require a USB-connected print server 
for compatibility.

Intermittent connections often stem from IPv6 addressing. Assign a DHCP reservation using the printer's MAC 
address to ensure IP stability. Avoid link-local addresses for permanent mappings. If your printer supports static 
IPv6, use an address outside your router's DHCP range to prevent conflicts.

Connection failures may result from TLS certificate validation. Modern OS versions reject weak or expired 
certificates. Access the printer's web interface via its IP address and generate a new self-signed certificate using 
SHA-256 encryption, or install a certificate from a trusted local CA.

Verify network segmentation settings. Guest networks and client isolation features block device-to-device 
communication. Ensure printer and client share the same private network segment. Allow traffic on ports 9100 
(raw TCP), 631 (IPP), and 5353 (mDNS) if using VLANs.

For driverless printing, confirm IPP Everywhere over HTTPS is enabled on the printer. Use native OS printing 
dialogs rather than legacy manufacturer utilities. Update your operating system's print subsystem to ensure protocol compatibility.

When issues persist, power-cycle the printer and router, then test with a direct USB connection to isolate 
network-specific failures. Document firmware versions and network settings before making changes to enable clean rollback if needed.

